04249nam a22006495i 9781477317686DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018018115  a97814773176867 a10.7560/3176622doi  a(DE-B1597)588659  a(OCoLC)1269268892  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHD6509.H84bS68 2019 4aHD6509.H84bS68 2019 7aSOC0440002bisacsh04a331.4/78130921 aSowards, Stacey K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10a¡Sí, Ella Puede! :bThe Rhetorical Legacy of Dolores Huerta and the United Farm Workers /cStacey K. Sowards. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter 1 FARM WORKER ORGANIZING AND THE ADVENT OF THE UFW: 1900 TO 1993 -- tChapter 2 DOLORES HUERTA’S LIFE: INTERSECTIONAL HABITUS AS RHETORICAL AGENCY -- tChapter 3 LETTERS TO CÉSAR CHÁVEZ: BUILDING COLLABORATIVE AGENCY -- tChapter 4 MOTHERHOOD, FAMILIA, EMOTIONALITY: STRATEGIC USE OF GENDERED PUBLIC PERSONA -- tChapter 5 PUBLIC PERSONA OF DIFFERENTIAL BRAVERY THROUGH COLLABORATIVE EGALITARIANISM AND COURAGEOUS OPTIMISM -- tChapter 6 DOLORES HUERTA, ICONICITY, AND SOCIAL MOVEMENTS -- tEPILOGUE -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1950s, Latina activist Dolores Huerta has been a fervent leader and organizer in the struggle for farmworkers’ rights within the Latina/o community. A cofounder of the United Farm Workers union in the 1960s alongside César Chávez, Huerta was a union vice president for nearly four decades before starting her own foundation in the early 2000s. She continues to act as a dynamic speaker, passionate lobbyist, and dedicated figure for social and political change, but her crucial contributions and commanding presence have often been overshadowed by those of Chávez and other leaders in the Chicana/o movement. In this new study, Stacey K. Sowards closely examines Huerta’s rhetorical skills both in and out of the public eye and defines Huerta’s vital place within Chicana/o history. Referencing the theoretical works of Pierre Bourdieu, Chela Sandoval, Gloria Anzaldúa, and others, Sowards closely analyzes Huerta’s speeches, letters, and interviews. She shows how Huerta navigates the complex intersections of race, ethnicity, gender, language, and class through the myriad challenges faced by women activists of color. Sowards’s approach to studying Huerta’s rhetorical influence offers a unique perspective for understanding the transformative relationship between agency and social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican American women labor union membersvBiography. 0aMigrant agricultural laborersxLabor unionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen labor leaderszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31766240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477317686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477317686/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK